commentBody:
@Steven 

Interesting. My research shows that in both Hindi and Urdu (the two mutually intelligible languages sometimes referred to as Hindustani), the word for India is Bharat (or some approximation). 

Hyrule is a fictitious kingdom in a video game franchise, hypothesized to be based on India.

@Steven 

Huh?


Oh, Zelda!   Nice one!

@Laura Stratton 

I have two college degrees and I usually solve Natan Last’s New Yorker puzzles in about two-thirds of what this one took me. But yes, he sometimes fills those with a wide array of cultural (kulturalische?) references. 

(My apologies to anyone who speaks German.)

@Foster 
(oops! Speaking of hand-eye coordination) was far better than mine, so he beat the bosses and I found the loot. Noteworthy clues today with this clever puzzle. 

Well done, puzzlers!

@Hub yes, you are the only one.

Jk!  

Both HEP and BERLE are oldies, like me, though Uncle Milty’s heyday was a bit before my time. He’s in  It’s a Mad, Mad, Mad, Mad World, which can be seen on TCM from time to time, with a lot of other old-time comedians and Spencer Tracy.

@Mark P 
Civilizations may be referred to as 'cultures'...for which KULTUR is a cognate.

A nice gimme.

@Nancy 

I struggled with this and finally gave up, too. There was just too much I didn't know, and bailed on the puzzle after filling in less than a quarter. Not fun at all.

I also find it hard to believe that someone could have solved this in 15 minutes with no lookups.

@C-64 

I looked up the Milton Berle character in IMDb. (I watched the show when it was first aired.)

It turns out that Louie the Lilac was in five episodes. That’s hardly on a par with the Joker or a similar villain.

@Steve L See? Steve L gets it!

Thanks for the bit assist.




cc: emu handler

@Mike 
What a card!  I have to give you credit for that.


No help from the emus, though.

@Darcey O’D 

The site xwstats.com rates the puzzle as “Very Hard,” based on the site’s users’ median solving time as compared to their average Saturday solving times for the preceding 60 days. 

I expect the people who have accounts there are generally faster than the average solver. But as of 9:40 CST Saturday, the median solving time is 20:09. I expect that will get longer as the day goes on.

@Hub at the ripe old age of 57 (😉) even I am not old enough to have experienced HEP when it was in popular usage, or seen Milton BERLE in his heyday, but at least I knew them from older movies (especially musicals) and syndicated TV. I can easily understand how anyone 40 or below might never have experienced either. Soon (if not already) even “hip” (which was probably out of fashion as a slang term by the early 80s) will be as unknown as HEP to the younger set. 

But try and remember HEP for future reference, it is not an infrequent visitor to the NYTxw.  🤓

If the movies I watched as a youth are to be believed, a “with it” guy (who was probably a jazz musician) might be known as a “hep cat”.  😊
